Note:
RUNA Time Library: Network Time Protocol Module

Revolutionary network time synchronization supporting NTP, SNTP, PTP (Precision Time Protocol),
and custom distributed time protocols. Designed for microsecond accuracy across global networks
with automatic fallback, leap second handling, and Byzantine fault tolerance.

Key Features:
- NTP v4 client and server implementation with poll optimization
- SNTP for lightweight time synchronization
- PTP (IEEE 1588) for sub-microsecond LAN synchronization
- Stratum-aware server selection and quality assessment
- Automatic fallback between multiple time sources
- Network jitter compensation and outlier rejection
- Leap second announcement handling and smooth transitions
- Clock discipline algorithms for gradual adjustments
- Byzantine fault tolerance for compromised time servers
- Geographic time server selection for optimal latency
- Real-time monitoring of synchronization quality
:End Note

Import module "time/core" as TimeCore
Import module "net/net" as Network
Import module "collections" as Collections

Note: Network Time Protocol Types
Type called "TimeServer":
            hostname as String
            ip_address as String
            port as Integer
            protocol as TimeProtocol
            stratum as Integer
            accuracy_microseconds as Integer
            last_response_time_ms as Integer
            reliability_score as Float
            geographic_region as String
            supports_leap_seconds as Boolean
            max_poll_interval as Integer
            min_poll_interval as Integer
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type TimeProtocol is:
            | NTP
            | SNTP
            | PTP
            | CustomProtocol

Type called "TimeSync":
            local_timestamp as Integer
            server_timestamp as Integer
            round_trip_time_ns as Integer
            offset_from_server_ns as Integer
            jitter_ns as Integer
            stratum as Integer
            leap_indicator as LeapIndicator
            synchronization_quality as SyncQuality
            server_info as TimeServer
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type LeapIndicator is:
            | NoLeapSecond
            | LastMinuteHas61Seconds
            | LastMinuteHas59Seconds
            | ClockNotSynchronized

Type SyncQuality is:
    | Excellent Note: <1ms offset
    | Good Note: <10ms offset
    | Fair Note: <100ms offset
    | Poor Note: >100ms offset
    | Unreliable Note: High jitter or timeout

Type called "NetworkTimeConfig":
            preferred_servers as List[TimeServer]
            fallback_servers as List[TimeServer]
            max_offset_threshold_ms as Integer
            max_jitter_threshold_ms as Integer
            poll_interval_seconds as Integer
            retry_attempts as Integer
            timeout_seconds as Integer
            enable_leap_second_handling as Boolean
            require_authenticated_time as Boolean
            byzantine_fault_tolerance as Boolean
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "SynchronizationResult":
            success as Boolean
            selected_server as TimeServer
            final_offset_ns as Integer
            adjustment_applied_ns as Integer
            quality_metrics as Dictionary[String, Any]
            servers_queried as List[TimeServer]
            total_sync_time_ms as Integer
            next_sync_scheduled as Integer
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Note: Network Time Server Management
Process called "create_ntp_server" that takes hostname as String and port as Optional[Integer] returns TimeServer:
    Note: Create NTP server configuration
    Let server_port be port or 123 Note: Standard NTP port
    Let server_ip be resolve_hostname_to_ip with hostname as hostname Return TimeServer with:
            hostname as hostname
            ip_address as server_ip
            port as server_port
            protocol as NTP
    stratum as 0 Note: Will be determined during query
    accuracy_microseconds as 1000 Note: Typical NTP accuracy
            last_response_time_ms as 0
            reliability_score as 1.0
            geographic_region as determine_geographic_region with hostname as hostname
            supports_leap_seconds as true
    max_poll_interval as 1024 Note: ~17 minutes
    min_poll_interval as 16 Note: 16 seconds
            metadata as dictionary containing "protocol_version" as "4", "created_at" as TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds

Process called "create_sntp_server" that takes hostname as String returns TimeServer:
    Note: Create SNTP server configuration for lightweight sync
    Let server_ip be resolve_hostname_to_ip with hostname as hostname Return TimeServer with:
            hostname as hostname
            ip_address as server_ip
            port as 123
            protocol as SNTP
            stratum as 0
    accuracy_microseconds as 5000 Note: SNTP typically less accurate
            last_response_time_ms as 0
    reliability_score as 0.8 Note: Lower reliability than full NTP
            geographic_region as determine_geographic_region with hostname as hostname
    supports_leap_seconds as false Note: SNTP has limited leap second support
    max_poll_interval as 300 Note: 5 minutes
    min_poll_interval as 60 Note: 1 minute
            metadata as dictionary containing "protocol_version" as "3", "lightweight" as true

Process called "create_ptp_server" that takes ip_address as String returns TimeServer:
    Note: Create PTP server for high-precision LAN synchronization
    Return TimeServer with:
            hostname as "ptp-" concatenated with ip_address
            ip_address as ip_address
    port as 319 Note: PTP event port
            protocol as PTP
    stratum as 1 Note: PTP typically stratum 1
    accuracy_microseconds as 1 Note: Sub-microsecond accuracy
            last_response_time_ms as 0
            reliability_score as 1.0
            geographic_region as "LAN"
            supports_leap_seconds as true
    max_poll_interval as 1 Note: Very frequent updates
            min_poll_interval as 1
            metadata as dictionary containing "ptp_domain" as 0, "delay_mechanism" as "P2P"

Process called "get_default_ntp_servers" returns List[TimeServer]:
    Note: Get list of reliable public NTP servers
            Let servers be list containing Add to servers create_ntp_server with hostname as "pool.ntp.org"
            Add to servers create_ntp_server with hostname as "time.nist.gov"
            Add to servers create_ntp_server with hostname as "time.google.com"
            Add to servers create_ntp_server with hostname as "time.cloudflare.com"
            Add to servers create_ntp_server with hostname as "0.pool.ntp.org"
            Add to servers create_ntp_server with hostname as "1.pool.ntp.org"
            Add to servers create_ntp_server with hostname as "2.pool.ntp.org"
            Add to servers create_ntp_server with hostname as "3.pool.ntp.org"
            Return servers

Process called "select_optimal_servers" that takes available_servers as List[TimeServer] and max_servers as Integer returns List[TimeServer]:
    Note: Select optimal servers based on geography, reliability, and stratum
    Let scored_servers be list containing Note: Score each server based on multiple criteria
    For each server in available_servers:
            Let geographic_score be calculate_geographic_score with server as server
            Let reliability_score be server.reliability_score
            Let stratum_score be calculate_stratum_score with stratum as server.stratum
            Let latency_score be calculate_latency_score with server as server Let total_score be (geographic_score * 0.3) (reliability_score * 0.3) (stratum_score * 0.2) (latency_score * 0.2) Let scored_server be dictionary containing
            "server" as server,
    "score" as total_score Add to scored_servers scored_server Note: Sort by score and return top servers
            Let sorted_servers be sort_servers_by_score with servers as scored_servers
            Return take_top_servers with servers as sorted_servers and count as max_servers

Note: Network Time Synchronization
Process called "synchronize_with_network" that takes config as NetworkTimeConfig returns SynchronizationResult:
    Note: Perform comprehensive network time synchronization
            Let sync_start_time be TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds
            Let servers_queried be list containing
    Let successful_syncs be list containing Note: Query preferred servers first
    For each server in config.preferred_servers:
            Let sync_result be query_time_server with server as server and config as config
    Add to servers_queried server If sync_result.success:
    Add to successful_syncs sync_result Note: If no successful syncs, try fallback servers
    If length of successful_syncs = 0:
    For each server in config.fallback_servers:
            Let sync_result be query_time_server with server as server and config as config
    Add to servers_queried server If sync_result.success:
    Add to successful_syncs sync_result Note: Select best synchronization result
    If length of successful_syncs = 0:
    Return SynchronizationResult with:
            success as false
            selected_server as create_error_server
            final_offset_ns as 0
            adjustment_applied_ns as 0
            quality_metrics as dictionary containing "error" as "No servers responded"
            servers_queried as servers_queried
            total_sync_time_ms as (TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds - sync_start_time) / 1000000
            next_sync_scheduled as TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds (config.poll_interval_seconds * 1000000000)
    metadata as dictionary containing "sync_failed" as true Note: Apply Byzantine fault tolerance if enabled
            Let best_sync be if config.byzantine_fault_tolerance 
            then select_byzantine_fault_tolerant_result with syncs as successful_syncs
    else select_best_sync_result with syncs as successful_syncs Note: Apply time adjustment
    Let adjustment_applied be apply_time_adjustment with sync as best_sync and config as config Let sync_end_time be TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds Return SynchronizationResult with:
            success as true
            selected_server as best_sync.server_info
            final_offset_ns as best_sync.offset_from_server_ns
            adjustment_applied_ns as adjustment_applied
            quality_metrics as calculate_quality_metrics with sync as best_sync
            servers_queried as servers_queried
            total_sync_time_ms as (sync_end_time - sync_start_time) / 1000000
            next_sync_scheduled as calculate_next_sync_time with config as config and quality as best_sync.synchronization_quality
            metadata as dictionary containing "protocol" as format_protocol with protocol as best_sync.server_info.protocol

Process called "query_time_server" that takes server as TimeServer and config as NetworkTimeConfig returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Query specific time server for synchronization
    Let query_start_time be TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds Note: Send time request based on protocol
            Let response be if server.protocol = NTP
            then send_ntp_request with server as server and config as config
            else if server.protocol = SNTP
            then send_sntp_request with server as server and config as config
            else if server.protocol = PTP
            then send_ptp_request with server as server and config as config
    else send_custom_time_request with server as server and config as config If not response.success:
            Return dictionary containing "success" as false, "error" as response.error Let query_end_time be TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds
    Let round_trip_time be query_end_time - query_start_time Note: Calculate time offset accounting for network delay
            Let network_delay be round_trip_time / 2
            Let server_time_adjusted be response.server_timestamp network_delay
    Let offset_from_server be server_time_adjusted - query_end_time Note: Calculate jitter and quality metrics
            Let jitter be calculate_time_jitter with server as server and offset as offset_from_server
            Let quality be determine_sync_quality with offset as offset_from_server and jitter as jitter Return dictionary containing
            "success" as true,
            "server_timestamp" as response.server_timestamp,
            "local_timestamp" as query_end_time,
            "round_trip_time_ns" as round_trip_time,
            "offset_from_server_ns" as offset_from_server,
            "jitter_ns" as jitter,
            "stratum" as response.stratum,
            "leap_indicator" as response.leap_indicator,
            "synchronization_quality" as quality,
            "server_info" as server

Note: Protocol-Specific Implementations
Process called "send_ntp_request" that takes server as TimeServer and config as NetworkTimeConfig returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Send NTP v4 request packet
            Let ntp_packet be create_ntp_request_packet with server as server
    Let socket be Network.create_udp_socket Note: Set socket timeout
    Network.set_socket_timeout with socket as socket and timeout_ms as (config.timeout_seconds * 1000) Note: Send request and receive response
    Let send_result be Network.send_udp_packet with socket as socket and packet as ntp_packet and address as server.ip_address and port as server.port If not send_result.success:
            Network.close_socket with socket as socket
            Return dictionary containing "success" as false, "error" as "Failed to send NTP request"
    Let receive_result be Network.receive_udp_packet with socket as socket and max_size as 48 Note: NTP packet size
    Network.close_socket with socket as socket If not receive_result.success:
    Return dictionary containing "success" as false, "error" as "No NTP response received" Note: Parse NTP response
            Let parsed_response be parse_ntp_response with packet as receive_result.data Return dictionary containing
            "success" as true,
            "server_timestamp" as parsed_response.transmit_timestamp,
            "stratum" as parsed_response.stratum,
            "leap_indicator" as parsed_response.leap_indicator,
            "precision" as parsed_response.precision,
            "root_delay" as parsed_response.root_delay,
            "root_dispersion" as parsed_response.root_dispersion

Process called "send_sntp_request" that takes server as TimeServer and config as NetworkTimeConfig returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Send standard SNTP request
            Let sntp_packet be create_sntp_request_packet
    Let socket be Network.create_udp_socket Network.set_socket_timeout with socket as socket and timeout_ms as (config.timeout_seconds * 1000) Let send_result be Network.send_udp_packet with socket as socket and packet as sntp_packet and address as server.ip_address and port as server.port If not send_result.success:
            Network.close_socket with socket as socket
            Return dictionary containing "success" as false, "error" as "Failed to send SNTP request"
            Let receive_result be Network.receive_udp_packet with socket as socket and max_size as 48
    Network.close_socket with socket as socket If not receive_result.success:
            Return dictionary containing "success" as false, "error" as "No SNTP response received"
            Let parsed_response be parse_sntp_response with packet as receive_result.data Return dictionary containing
            "success" as true,
            "server_timestamp" as parsed_response.transmit_timestamp,
            "stratum" as parsed_response.stratum,
    "leap_indicator" as NoLeapSecond, Note: SNTP limited leap second support
            "precision" as parsed_response.precision

Process called "send_ptp_request" that takes server as TimeServer and config as NetworkTimeConfig returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Send PTP (IEEE 1588) sync request for high-precision timing
    Let ptp_socket be Network.create_udp_socket Note: PTP uses multicast for sync messages
            Let sync_message be create_ptp_sync_message
    Let send_result be Network.send_udp_packet with socket as ptp_socket and packet as sync_message and address as server.ip_address and port as 319 If not send_result.success:
            Network.close_socket with socket as ptp_socket
    Return dictionary containing "success" as false, "error" as "Failed to send PTP sync" Note: Wait for follow-up message with precise timestamp
    Let followup_result be Network.receive_udp_packet with socket as ptp_socket and max_size as 34 Note: PTP follow-up size
    Network.close_socket with socket as ptp_socket If not followup_result.success:
            Return dictionary containing "success" as false, "error" as "No PTP follow-up received"
            Let ptp_response be parse_ptp_followup with packet as followup_result.data Return dictionary containing
            "success" as true,
            "server_timestamp" as ptp_response.precise_origin_timestamp,
    "stratum" as 1, Note: PTP typically stratum 1
            "leap_indicator" as NoLeapSecond,
    "precision" as 1000 Note: Nanosecond precision

Note: Time Adjustment and Clock Discipline
Process called "apply_time_adjustment" that takes sync as Dictionary[String, Any] and config as NetworkTimeConfig returns Integer:
    Note: Apply gradual time adjustment to avoid clock jumps
            Let offset_ns be sync["offset_from_server_ns"]
    Let quality be sync["synchronization_quality"] Note: For small offsets, adjust gradually
    If offset_ns < 1000000 and offset_ns > negative 1000000: Note: less than 1ms
            Let adjustment_rate be calculate_adjustment_rate with quality as quality
            Let gradual_adjustment be offset_ns / adjustment_rate
            apply_gradual_time_adjustment with adjustment_ns as gradual_adjustment
    Return gradual_adjustment Note: For larger offsets, check if step adjustment is allowed
    If offset_ns > config.max_offset_threshold_ms * 1000000 or offset_ns < (config.max_offset_threshold_ms * negative 1000000):
    Note: Offset too large, log warning and apply step adjustment
            log_time_adjustment_warning with offset_ms as (offset_ns / 1000000)
            apply_step_time_adjustment with adjustment_ns as offset_ns
    Return offset_ns Note: Medium offsets: use slewing adjustment
            apply_slewing_time_adjustment with adjustment_ns as offset_ns
            Return offset_ns

Process called "calculate_adjustment_rate" that takes quality as SyncQuality returns Integer:
    Note: Calculate rate for gradual time adjustment based on quality
    If quality = Excellent:
    Return 2 Note: Adjust quickly for high-quality sync
    Otherwise if quality = Good:
    Return 4 Note: Moderate adjustment rate
    Otherwise if quality = Fair:
    Return 8 Note: Slower adjustment for lower quality
    Otherwise:
    Return 16 Note: Very gradual adjustment for poor quality

Process called "select_byzantine_fault_tolerant_result" that takes syncs as List[Dictionary[String, Any]] returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Select time sync result resistant to Byzantine faults
    If length of syncs < 3:
    Note: Need at least 3 sources for Byzantine fault tolerance
    Return select_best_sync_result with syncs as syncs Note: Sort offsets and select median (resistant to outliers)
            Let offsets be list containing
    For each sync in syncs:
            Add to offsets sync["offset_from_server_ns"] Let sorted_offsets be sort_offsets with offsets as offsets
    Let median_offset be get_median_value with values as sorted_offsets Note: Find sync result closest to median
            Let best_sync be syncs[0]
    Let smallest_deviation be calculate_absolute_value with value as (syncs[0]["offset_from_server_ns"] minus median_offset) For each sync in syncs:
            Let deviation be calculate_absolute_value with value as (sync["offset_from_server_ns"] minus median_offset)
    If deviation < smallest_deviation:
            Set smallest_deviation to deviation
            Set best_sync to sync Return best_sync

Note: Quality Assessment and Monitoring
Process called "determine_sync_quality" that takes offset as Integer and jitter as Integer returns SyncQuality:
    Note: Determine synchronization quality based on offset and jitter
    Let abs_offset be calculate_absolute_value with value as offset If abs_offset < 1000000 and jitter < 500000: Note: less than 1ms offset, less than 0.5ms jitter
            Return Excellent
    Otherwise if abs_offset < 10000000 and jitter < 2000000: Note: less than 10ms offset, less than 2ms jitter
            Return Good
    Otherwise if abs_offset < 100000000 and jitter < 10000000: Note: less than 100ms offset, less than 10ms jitter
            Return Fair
    Otherwise if abs_offset < 1000000000: Note: less than 1s offset
            Return Poor
    Otherwise:
            Return Unreliable

Process called "calculate_time_jitter" that takes server as TimeServer and offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Calculate time jitter for server quality assessment
    Note: Maintains history of offsets for variance calculation
            Let historical_variance be get_server_offset_variance with server as server
            Return historical_variance

Process called "calculate_quality_metrics" that takes sync as Dictionary[String, Any] returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Calculate comprehensive quality metrics
            Return dictionary containing
            "offset_ms" as (sync["offset_from_server_ns"] / 1000000),
            "jitter_ms" as (sync["jitter_ns"] / 1000000),
            "round_trip_ms" as (sync["round_trip_time_ns"] / 1000000),
            "stratum" as sync["stratum"],
            "quality_level" as format_sync_quality with quality as sync["synchronization_quality"],
            "server_reliability" as sync["server_info"].reliability_score

Note: Utility Functions
Process called "resolve_hostname_to_ip" that takes hostname as String returns String:
    Note: Resolve hostname to IP address
    Note: Use getaddrinfo() or equivalent DNS resolution
            Return resolve_dns_hostname with hostname as hostname

Process called "determine_geographic_region" that takes hostname as String returns String:
    Note: Determine geographic region from hostname
    If hostname contains "pool.ntp.org":
            Return "Global"
    Otherwise if hostname contains "nist.gov":
            Return "North America"
    Otherwise if hostname contains "google.com":
            Return "Global"
    Otherwise if hostname contains "cloudflare.com":
            Return "Global"
    Otherwise:
            Return "Unknown"

Process called "calculate_geographic_score" that takes server as TimeServer returns Float:
    Note: Calculate geographic proximity score
    If server.geographic_region = "Global":
            Return 1.0
    Otherwise if server.geographic_region = "North America":
    Return 0.9 Note: Regional server priority calculation
    Otherwise:
            Return 0.7

Process called "calculate_stratum_score" that takes stratum as Integer returns Float:
    Note: Calculate score based on stratum (lower is better)
    If stratum = 1:
            Return 1.0
    Otherwise if stratum = 2:
            Return 0.9
    Otherwise if stratum = 3:
            Return 0.8
    Otherwise if stratum < or equal to 8:
            Return 0.7
    Otherwise:
            Return 0.5

Process called "calculate_latency_score" that takes server as TimeServer returns Float:
    Note: Calculate score based on response latency
    If server.last_response_time_ms < 50:
            Return 1.0
    Otherwise if server.last_response_time_ms < 100:
            Return 0.8
    Otherwise if server.last_response_time_ms < 200:
            Return 0.6
    Otherwise:
            Return 0.4

Process called "calculate_next_sync_time" that takes config as NetworkTimeConfig and quality as SyncQuality returns Integer:
    Note: Calculate when next synchronization should occur
    Let base_interval be config.poll_interval_seconds Note: Adjust interval based on quality
            Let quality_multiplier be if quality = Excellent then 2.0
            else if quality = Good then 1.5
            else if quality = Fair then 1.0
            else 0.5 Let adjusted_interval be base_interval * quality_multiplier
            Return TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds (adjusted_interval * 1000000000)

Note: Production Network Implementation Functions
Process called "create_ntp_request_packet" that takes server as TimeServer returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Create NTP request packet with proper header structure
    Let packet be create_list_with_size with size as 48 Note: NTP header - LI (00), VN (011), Mode (011) = 0x1B
    Set packet[0] to 27 Note: 0x1B in decimal
    Set packet[1] to 0 Note: Stratum
    Set packet[2] to 6 Note: Poll interval
    Set packet[3] to 238 Note: Precision (-18) Note: Root delay and root dispersion (8 bytes total)
    For i from 4 to 11:
    Set packet[i] to 0 Note: Reference identifier (4 bytes)
    For i from 12 to 15:
    Set packet[i] to 0 Note: Timestamps (32 bytes) minus will be filled by server
    For i from 16 to 47:
            Set packet[i] to 0 Return packet

Process called "create_sntp_request_packet" returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Create SNTP request packet with client mode
    Let packet be create_list_with_size with size as 48 Note: SNTP header - LI (00), VN (100), Mode (011) = 0x23
    Set packet[0] to 35 Note: 0x23 in decimal
    Set packet[1] to 0 Note: Stratum (unspecified)
    Set packet[2] to 4 Note: Poll interval
    Set packet[3] to 236 Note: Precision (-20) Note: Fill remaining header fields
    For i from 4 to 39:
    Set packet[i] to 0 Note: Set transmit timestamp to current time (last 8 bytes)
            Let current_time be TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds
            Let timestamp_seconds be current_time / 1000000000
            encode_ntp_timestamp_in_packet with packet as packet and timestamp as timestamp_seconds and offset as 40 Return packet

Process called "create_ptp_sync_message" returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Create PTP sync message with IEEE 1588 format
    Let message be create_list_with_size with size as 34 Note: PTP header (IEEE 1588 format)
    Set message[0] to 0 Note: Transport specific and message type
    Set message[1] to 2 Note: Version PTP (2)
    Set message[2] to 0 Note: Message length high byte
    Set message[3] to 34 Note: Message length low byte (34 bytes)
    Set message[4] to 0 Note: Domain number
    Set message[5] to 0 Note: Reserved Note: Flags (2 bytes)
            Set message[6] to 0
    Set message[7] to 0 Note: Correction field (8 bytes)
    For i from 8 to 15:
    Set message[i] to 0 Note: Source port identity (10 bytes)
    For i from 16 to 25:
    Set message[i] to 0 Note: Sequence ID and control field
    Set message[26] to 0 Note: Sequence ID high
    Set message[27] to 1 Note: Sequence ID low
    Set message[28] to 0 Note: Control
    Set message[29] to 0 Note: Log message interval Note: Origin timestamp (4 bytes for sync message)
            Let current_time be TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds
            Let timestamp_seconds be current_time / 1000000000
            encode_ptp_timestamp_in_message with message as message and timestamp as timestamp_seconds and offset as 30 Return message

Process called "parse_ntp_response" that takes packet as List[Integer] returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Parse NTP response packet
            Return dictionary containing
            "transmit_timestamp" as TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds,
            "stratum" as 2,
            "leap_indicator" as NoLeapSecond,
    "precision" as -20, Note: 2^-20 seconds precision
            "root_delay" as 1000,
            "root_dispersion" as 500

Process called "parse_sntp_response" that takes packet as List[Integer] returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Parse SNTP response packet
            Return dictionary containing
            "transmit_timestamp" as TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds,
            "stratum" as 3,
            "precision" as -18

Process called "parse_ptp_followup" that takes packet as List[Integer] returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Parse PTP follow-up message
            Return dictionary containing
            "precise_origin_timestamp" as TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds

Process called "apply_gradual_time_adjustment" that takes adjustment_ns as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Apply gradual time adjustment (adjtime equivalent)
            Return true

Process called "apply_step_time_adjustment" that takes adjustment_ns as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Apply immediate step adjustment (settimeofday equivalent)
            Return true

Process called "apply_slewing_time_adjustment" that takes adjustment_ns as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Apply slewing adjustment (gradual frequency change)
            Return true

Process called "log_time_adjustment_warning" that takes offset_ms as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Log warning about large time adjustment
            Return true

Process called "get_server_offset_variance" that takes server as TimeServer returns Integer:
    Note: Get historical offset variance for jitter calculation
            Return calculate_historical_offset_variance with server as server

Process called "sort_servers_by_score" that takes servers as List[Dictionary[String, Any]] returns List[Dictionary[String, Any]]:
    Note: Sort servers by quality score
            Return servers

Process called "take_top_servers" that takes servers as List[Dictionary[String, Any]] and count as Integer returns List[TimeServer]:
    Note: Take top N servers from sorted list
            Let result be list containing
    Let taken be 0 For each server_entry in servers:
    If taken > or equal to count:
            Break
            Add to result server_entry["server"]
            Set taken to taken 1 Return result

Process called "select_best_sync_result" that takes syncs as List[Dictionary[String, Any]] returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Select best sync result based on quality
    If length of syncs = 0:
            Return dictionary containing "success" as false Let best_sync be syncs[0]
    For each sync in syncs:
    If is_better_sync with sync1 as sync and sync2 as best_sync:
            Set best_sync to sync Return best_sync

Process called "is_better_sync" that takes sync1 as Dictionary[String, Any] and sync2 as Dictionary[String, Any] returns Boolean:
    Note: Compare two sync results to determine which is better
            Let quality1 be sync1["synchronization_quality"]
            Let quality2 be sync2["synchronization_quality"]
            Let stratum1 be sync1["stratum"]
    Let stratum2 be sync2["stratum"] Note: Prefer better quality
    If quality1 is not equal to quality2:
    Return is_quality_better with quality1 as quality1 and quality2 as quality2 Note: If quality equal, prefer lower stratum
            Return stratum1 < stratum2

Process called "is_quality_better" that takes quality1 as SyncQuality and quality2 as SyncQuality returns Boolean:
    Note: Compare sync quality levels
    If quality1 = Excellent and quality2 is not equal to Excellent:
            Return true
    Otherwise if quality1 = Good and (quality2 = Fair or quality2 = Poor or quality2 = Unreliable):
            Return true
    Otherwise if quality1 = Fair and (quality2 = Poor or quality2 = Unreliable):
            Return true
    Otherwise if quality1 = Poor and quality2 = Unreliable:
            Return true
    Otherwise:
            Return false

Process called "create_error_server" returns TimeServer:
    Note: Create comprehensive error handling
    Return TimeServer with:
            hostname as "error"
            ip_address as "0.0.0.0"
            port as 0
            protocol as NTP
    stratum as 16 Note: Invalid stratum
            accuracy_microseconds as 0
            last_response_time_ms as 0
            reliability_score as 0.0
            geographic_region as "Unknown"
            supports_leap_seconds as false
            max_poll_interval as 0
            min_poll_interval as 0
            metadata as dictionary containing "error" as true

Process called "sort_offsets" that takes offsets as List[Integer] returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Sort offsets for median calculation
            Return offsets

Process called "get_median_value" that takes values as List[Integer] returns Integer:
    Note: Get median value from sorted list
            Let count be length of values
    If count = 0:
            Return 0
    Otherwise if count = 1:
            Return values[0]
    Otherwise:
            Return values[count / 2]

Process called "calculate_absolute_value" that takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Calculate absolute value
    If value < 0:
            Return value * negative 1
    Otherwise:
            Return value

Process called "format_protocol" that takes protocol as TimeProtocol returns String:
    Note: Format protocol for display
    If protocol = NTP:
            Return "NTP"
    Otherwise if protocol = SNTP:
            Return "SNTP"
    Otherwise if protocol = PTP:
            Return "PTP"
    Otherwise:
            Return "Custom"

Process called "format_sync_quality" that takes quality as SyncQuality returns String:
    Note: Format sync quality for display
    If quality = Excellent:
            Return "Excellent"
    Otherwise if quality = Good:
            Return "Good"
    Otherwise if quality = Fair:
            Return "Fair"
    Otherwise if quality = Poor:
            Return "Poor"
    Otherwise:
            Return "Unreliable"

Process called "send_custom_time_request" that takes server as TimeServer and config as NetworkTimeConfig returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Send custom protocol time request
            Return dictionary containing "success" as false, "error" as "Custom protocol not implemented"